Trump and the economy
New York – The financial markets have finally woken up, and it turns out that Trump is the President of the United States.
The world has endured this person with the most power in the world for two years of unbridled Twitter and public statements, and it is obvious what kept it going for so long?
On one hand, until now, investors have been giving Trump the benefit of the doubt.
As long as he implements tax cuts, deregulation, and other policies beneficial to the corporate sector and shareholders, they will continue to give him the benefit of the doubt.
Many people believe that in the end, "the adults in the room" will restrain Trump, ensuring government policies remain within bounds.
Such an assumption was somewhat validated during Trump's first year in office, a period during which economic growth and corporate profit expectations increased — thanks to impending tax cuts and deregulation — leading to a strong stock market performance.
In 2017, the US stock market index rose by over 20%.
However, in 2018, the situation took a sharp turn downward, especially in the last few months.
Although corporate profits increased by over 20% (thanks to tax cuts), the US stock market was volatile for most of the year and is now plummeting sharply.
Currently, all indices are located in the correction zone (10% below the recent high), and the tech stock index (such as Nasdaq) has fallen into a bear market (down 20% or more).
Although the increased volatility of financial markets reflects concerns about China, Italy, and other Eurozone economies, as well as key emerging economies, the recent turmoil is due to Trump.
At the beginning of the year, Trump implemented a reckless tax cut, which led to rising long-term interest rates and a peak in the economy that was already near full employment.
By February, concerns about inflation rising above the Federal Reserve's target of 2% led to the first wave of safe-haven buying in 2018.
Then, Trump launched a trade war against China and other important US trading partners.
Market concerns about the government's protectionist policies have fluctuated throughout the year, but are now reaching a new peak.
The US's recent actions against China seem to be preparing for a comprehensive trade, economic, and geopolitical Cold War.
Another concern is that Trump's other policies will bring about a stagflation effect (growth slows down while inflation increases).
After all, Trump is planning to restrict foreign direct investment and has implemented broad immigration restrictions, which will drag down the growth of labor supply in a situation where labor is aging and skills are misaligned.
Furthermore, the Trump administration has not yet proposed plans to stimulate private sector productivity or accelerate the transition to a green economy through infrastructure projects.
In Twitter and other contexts, Trump constantly criticizes companies' hiring, production, investment, and pricing practices, especially those of tech enterprises, which have faced widespread opposition and increasingly fierce competition from Chinese rivals.
New emerging markets have also been affected by US policies.
Fiscal stimulus and monetary policy tightening have pushed up short-term and long-term interest rates, strengthening the US dollar.
As a result, emerging economies have faced capital flight and an increase in the value of dollar-denominated debt.
Emerging economies heavily reliant on exports have suffered losses due to the decline in commodity prices, and even countries with only indirect trade relations with China have felt the impact of the trade war.
Even Trump's oil policy has created volatility.
The US re-imposition of sanctions on Iran drove up oil prices, followed by a sharp drop after the US government canceled exemptions and threatened Saudi Arabia to increase oil production.
Although American consumers benefited from low oil prices, the stock prices of US energy companies could not withstand it.
Furthermore, excessive oil price volatility is detrimental to both producers and consumers, as it hinders wise investment and consumption decisions.
Worse still, it is now clear that the benefits of last year's tax cut have almost entirely flowed to the corporate sector, rather than in the form of higher real (inflation-adjusted) wages to households.
This means that household consumption may soon slow down, further affecting the economy.
However, the main reason for the recent sharp decline in the US and global stock markets is Trump's own rhetoric and actions.
Worse than the prominent risk of a full-scale trade war with China (although he recently reached a "ceasefire" with Chinese President Xi Jinping) is Trump's public attacks on the Federal Reserve. His attacks began in the spring of 2018, when the US economic growth rate was above 4%.
Due to these early attacks, the market became a "paralyzed bird" when the Federal Reserve correctly decided to raise interest rates this month, implying that it would raise rates more slowly in 2019.
More likely, the Federal Reserve's relatively hawkish stance is a reaction to Trump's attacks on it.
Facing an antagonistic president on Twitter, Federal Reserve Chairman Jerome Powell needs to send a signal that the central bank still maintains its political independence.
But then, because Congress refused to allocate funds for Trump's useless Mexico border wall, Trump decided to partially shut down the federal government.
This move pushed the market into a near-panic state, and as the government shutdown progressed, there were reports that Trump wanted to fire Powell – which could have led the market correction to collapse.
On the eve of the Christmas holiday, US Treasury Secretary Steven Mnuchin was forced to issue a public statement to calm the market.
He claimed that Trump had no plan to fire Powell, and that the US financial situation was good – which only highlighted the question of whether it was really good.
While recent government personnel changes may not necessarily affect economic decision-making, they have still caused concern in the market.
The impending departure of White House Chief of Staff John Kelly and Secretary of Defense James Mattis from the Trump administration has left the cabinet without any rational voices.
Those remaining will all be economic nationalists and hawkish diplomats, with Trump at the forefront.
The possibility of a full-scale geoeconomic conflict with China cannot be ruled out.
A new Cold War could lead to deglobalization and destroy global supply chains, but the tech industry will be the first to suffer, as recent cases against Huawei and ZTE have shown.
At the same time, Trump seems determined to undermine the unity of the EU and NATO during a time of European economic and political instability.
The investigation by special prosecutor Robert Mueller into Trump's 2016 presidential campaign ties to Russia is the Damocles sword hanging over the president's career.
Trump is now the market's Dr. Strangelove.
Like the paranoid madman in Stanley Kubrick's classic film, he is trapped in a self-destructive cycle of economic ruin.
Today, the market sees this danger and the risk of financial crises and global recession is rising steadily.
